24
00:02:15,640 --> 00:02:21,140
" <i>Wait along,
wait along</i> "

25
00:02:21,640 --> 00:02:29,140
" <i>Wait along,
wait alooong</i> "

26
00:02:48,140 --> 00:02:54,140
[Church bell ringing]

27
00:03:58,540 --> 00:04:00,140
Did you see,
what I saw?

28
00:04:00,540 --> 00:04:04,140
C'mon Joe, open it up.
We're going to have a big day, today

29
00:04:11,145 --> 00:04:13,773
- You're in a hurry?
- Yeah, I sure am.

30
00:04:14,024 --> 00:04:16,860
You're a fool.
Come on.

31
00:04:21,115 --> 00:04:23,908
All right, all right, ladies and gentlemen.
Let us begin.

32
00:04:25,744 --> 00:04:29,123
Would the bride and groom
kindly step forward?

33
00:04:31,709 --> 00:04:33,627
Will Kane and Amy Fowler,

34
00:04:33,877 --> 00:04:38,549
you appear before me in my capacity
as Justice of the Peace of this township.

35
00:04:38,758 --> 00:04:42,428
To be joined together
in the bounds of holy matrimony.

36
00:04:49,102 --> 00:04:52,813
- Man, it sure is hot.
- Hot? You call this hot?

37
00:04:57,069 --> 00:04:59,060
- Well, I'll be...
- What's the matter?

38
00:04:59,160 --> 00:05:00,860
I thought I saw Ben Miller.

39
00:05:01,073 --> 00:05:04,117
- Ah, he's down Texas somewhere.
- I know.

40
00:05:04,284 --> 00:05:08,330
Looked like Pierce and Colby, too.
No, it couldn't be Miller.

41
00:05:27,933 --> 00:05:31,104
My goodness gracious

42
00:05:36,735 --> 00:05:42,282
- Noon train on time?
- Yes, sir. That is, I think so, sir.

43
00:05:42,491 --> 00:05:46,578
Don't know reason why
it shouldn't be...Mr Pierce.

44
00:05:46,828 --> 00:05:52,084
How're you,
Mr Miller... Mr Pierce... Mr Colby?

45
00:06:26,953 --> 00:06:30,207
Do you, Will Kane, take Amy
to be your lawful wedded wife,

46
00:06:30,374 --> 00:06:34,670
to have and to hold from this day forward,
until death do you part?

47
00:06:34,879 --> 00:06:36,214
I do.

48
00:06:36,421 --> 00:06:39,550
Do you Amy take Will
to be your lawful wedded husband

49
00:06:39,717 --> 00:06:44,305
to have and to hold from this day forward
until death do you part?

50
00:06:44,514 --> 00:06:47,767
- I do.
- The ring, please.

51
00:06:54,523 --> 00:06:58,404
Then by the authority invested in me
by the laws of this territory,

52
00:06:58,528 --> 00:07:02,532
I pronounce you
"man and wife".

53
00:07:07,330 --> 00:07:12,120
I can't speak for the rest of you men,
but I claim an ancient privilege.

54
00:07:19,300 --> 00:07:22,130
Moving mighty fast
for a Sunday.

55
00:07:25,264 --> 00:07:29,852
- Will!
- All those people...

56
00:07:30,896 --> 00:07:34,566
Amy, people ought to be alone
when they get married.

57
00:07:34,733 --> 00:07:36,818
I know.

58
00:07:36,985 --> 00:07:40,863
I'm gonna try, Amy.
I'll do my best.

59
00:07:41,949 --> 00:07:43,618
I will too.

60
00:07:49,832 --> 00:07:52,835
Honeymoon is officially over.
Come on, everybody.

61
00:07:53,043 --> 00:07:57,298
- Don't look so shocked.
- No privacy on his wedding day.

62
00:07:57,465 --> 00:08:02,763
Well, one more ceremony,
and Will's a free man, more or less.

63
00:08:02,928 --> 00:08:05,139
Marshal,
turn in your badge.

64
00:08:05,307 --> 00:08:08,851
To tell you the truth, I hate to do this
without your new Marshal being here.

65
00:08:09,061 --> 00:08:13,189
Will, Fuller, Haland, and  I are the entire board
of selectmen of this community.

66
00:08:13,482 --> 00:08:15,567
We're also
your very good friends.

67
00:08:15,774 --> 00:08:20,321
With the fine job you've done I feel free here
to say, and the judge will bare me out,

68
00:08:20,531 --> 00:08:23,030
this town will be safe
'til tomorrow.

69
00:08:24,284 --> 00:08:28,663
You win. But don't marry a Quaker,
she'll have you running a store.

70
00:08:28,873 --> 00:08:31,917
- I can't picture you doing that, Will
- I can.

71
00:08:32,126 --> 00:08:35,003
So can I,
and a good thing, too.

72
00:08:35,213 --> 00:08:37,089
Thank you.

73
00:08:37,256 --> 00:08:40,301
You didn't talk that way
when you were wearing a star.

74
00:08:41,470 --> 00:08:45,180
All right, it's coming off.
But I gotta to be paid first.

75
00:08:47,307 --> 00:08:50,729
- Let me down!
- Not until you kiss me.

76
00:08:50,978 --> 00:08:54,274
Will, let me down,
you fool!

77
00:09:01,270 --> 00:09:05,270
[Crowd claps]

78
00:09:06,620 --> 00:09:10,708
- You should have been a lawyer.
- I was meant to be a storekeeper.

79
00:09:10,916 --> 00:09:13,669
Marshal,
a telegram for you.

80
00:09:15,045 --> 00:09:17,799
It's terrible,
it's shocking.

81
00:09:19,675 --> 00:09:23,513
- They've pardoned Frank Miller.
- I don't believe it.

82
00:09:23,722 --> 00:09:25,890
We could go too.

83
00:09:26,057 --> 00:09:28,602
- Nice of them to let you know.
- And that ain't all.

84
00:09:28,851 --> 00:09:31,854
Ben Miller is down the depot now
with Jim Pierce and Jack Colby.

85
00:09:32,064 --> 00:09:35,317
- He asked about the noon train.
- The noon train?

86
00:09:38,279 --> 00:09:43,951
Will.. You get out of this town.
Get out of this town this very minute.

87
00:09:44,159 --> 00:09:49,122
- What is it?
- Never mind that now.

88
00:09:49,373 --> 00:09:50,720
But, what is it,
Mr Howe?

89
00:09:50,820 --> 00:09:54,420
Don't you worry. Just get out of town,
and everything will be alright.

90
00:09:55,080 --> 00:09:57,250
- We'll take care of everything.
- I think I ought to stay.

91
00:09:57,500 --> 00:10:00,710
Are you crazy?
Think of Amy.

92
00:10:03,345 --> 00:10:07,350
Goodbye, Amy.
Don't worry, everything will be alright

93
00:10:08,350 --> 00:10:10,350
Good luck, boy!
Hurry!

94
00:10:27,787 --> 00:10:29,123
Hm...
That's funny.

95
00:10:32,167 --> 00:10:35,130
- What?
- Oh, you can't see now.

96
00:10:35,880 --> 00:10:39,759
Kane and his new wife
just took off in a big hurry.

97
00:10:40,009 --> 00:10:43,304
- What's so funny?
- I mean, a big hurry.

98
00:10:44,097 --> 00:10:48,726
Hey, you don't suppose
Kane's scared of those three gunnies?

99
00:10:50,937 --> 00:10:54,357
I never saw him
whip a horse that way.

100
00:11:06,621 --> 00:11:09,039
- Sam?
- Come in, Helen.

101
00:11:09,248 --> 00:11:14,378
Ben Miller is in town.
He has two of the old bunch with him.

102
00:11:18,049 --> 00:11:21,093
I guess
I'll take a look around.

103
00:12:05,141 --> 00:12:08,351
- Why are you stopping?
- It's no good. I've got go back, Amy.

104
00:12:08,559 --> 00:12:11,729
- Why?
- This is crazy. I haven't got any guns.

105
00:12:11,980 --> 00:12:15,358
- Then let's go on. Hurry.
- No.

106
00:12:15,568 --> 00:12:17,485
That's what I've been thinking.

107
00:12:17,695 --> 00:12:20,406
They're making me run.
I've never run from anybody before.

108
00:12:20,614 --> 00:12:24,952
- I don't understand any of this.
- I don't have time to tell you.

109
00:12:25,160 --> 00:12:29,081
- Then don't go back, Will
- I've got to. That's the whole thing.

110
00:13:31,229 --> 00:13:32,939
Kane's back!

111
00:13:33,231 --> 00:13:35,568
- Don't believe it.
- Just seen him!

112
00:13:38,821 --> 00:13:40,906
- How many coffins have we got?
- Two.

113
00:13:41,115 --> 00:13:43,242
We'll need at least two more,
no matter how you figure it.

114
00:13:43,451 --> 00:13:45,494
You better get busy,
Fred.

115
00:13:48,038 --> 00:13:53,169
Please Will,
if you'd just tell me what this is all about.

116
00:13:53,377 --> 00:13:57,256
I sent a man up five years ago for murder.
He was supposed to hang.

117
00:13:57,507 --> 00:14:01,886
But up north, they commuted it to life
and now he's free.

118
00:14:02,053 --> 00:14:04,514
I don't know how.
It looks like he's coming back.

119
00:14:04,764 --> 00:14:06,891
- I still don't understand.
- He's a...

120
00:14:07,101 --> 00:14:12,064
He was always wild and kind of crazy.
He'll probably make trouble.

121
00:14:12,314 --> 00:14:15,484
But that's no concern of yours.
Not any more.

122
00:14:15,692 --> 00:14:17,778
I'm the one who sent him up.

123
00:14:17,987 --> 00:14:22,659
But that was part of your job. It's finished, now.
They've got a new Marshal

124
00:14:22,866 --> 00:14:27,831
He won't be here until tomorrow.
Seems to me I've got to stay.

125
00:14:28,039 --> 00:14:32,252
- Anyway, m the same man with or without this.
- That isn't so.

126
00:14:32,419 --> 00:14:36,047
I expect he'll come looking for me.
Three of his old bunch are waiting for him.

127
00:14:36,214 --> 00:14:39,885
- That's why we ought to go.
- They'll just come after us.

128
00:14:40,051 --> 00:14:44,180
Four of them...
And we'd be all alone in the prairie.

129
00:14:44,848 --> 00:14:46,683
- We've got an hour.
- What's an hour?

130
00:14:46,850 --> 00:14:50,228
It's a hundred miles. We'd never be able
to keep that store, Amy.

131
00:14:50,437 --> 00:14:53,023
They'd come after us. We'd have to run
again as long as we live.

132
00:14:53,231 --> 00:14:56,985
No, you wouldn't.
Not, if they didn't know where to find us.

133
00:14:58,571 --> 00:15:02,617
- I'm begging you, please, let's go.
- I can't.

134
00:15:02,825 --> 00:15:06,579
Don't try to be a hero.
You don't have to be a hero, not for me.

135
00:15:06,746 --> 00:15:10,499
I'm not not trying to be a hero.
If you think I like this, you're crazy.

136
00:15:10,666 --> 00:15:14,087
Look, Amy. This is my town.
I've got friends here.

137
00:15:14,253 --> 00:15:17,150
I'll swear in bunch of special deputies,
and with a posse behind me,

138
00:15:17,250 --> 00:15:18,750
maybe there won't be any trouble.

139
00:15:18,967 --> 00:15:23,305
- You know there'll be trouble.
- Then, it's better to have it here.

140
00:15:28,101 --> 00:15:30,771
I'm sorry, honey.
I know how you feel about it.

141
00:15:30,938 --> 00:15:35,401
- Do you?
- Of course I do. It's against your religion.

142
00:15:35,609 --> 00:15:40,406
- Sure I know how you feel
- But you're doing it just the same.

143
00:15:40,572 --> 00:15:45,203
Oh, Will..
We were married just a few minutes ago.

144
00:15:45,410 --> 00:15:49,708
We've got our whole lives ahead of us.
Doesn't that mean anything?

145
00:15:49,874 --> 00:15:53,420
You know I've only got an hour,
and I've got lots to do.

146
00:15:53,670 --> 00:15:55,964
Stay at the hotel
until it's over.

147
00:15:56,130 --> 00:15:58,467
No,
I won't be here when it's over.

148
00:15:58,674 --> 00:16:02,345
You're asking me to wait an hour to find out
if I'll be a wife or a widow.

149
00:16:02,512 --> 00:16:05,765
- It's too long to wait. I won't do it.
- Amy...

150
00:16:05,974 --> 00:16:10,354
I mean it. If you won't go with me now,
I'll be on that train when it leaves here.

151
00:16:11,980 --> 00:16:13,774
I've got to stay.

152
00:16:20,270 --> 00:16:25,270
" <i>On this,
our wedding daaayyy.</i>"

153
00:16:25,770 --> 00:16:30,770
" <i>Do not forsake me,
oh, my daaarlin',</i> "

154
00:16:31,270 --> 00:16:36,770
" <i>Although you're grievin',
I can't be leavin'</i>  "

155
00:16:37,006 --> 00:16:40,302
- Glad you got here, Percy.
- Are you?

156
00:16:51,939 --> 00:16:56,694
Have you forgotten that I'm the man that
passed sentence on Frank Miller?

157
00:16:56,860 --> 00:16:59,488
You shouldn't have come back,
Will

158
00:16:59,655 --> 00:17:03,368
I figured I had to.
I figured I had to stay.

159
00:17:03,533 --> 00:17:07,580
- You figured wrong.
- I can deputize a posse, 10-12 guns.

160
00:17:07,788 --> 00:17:11,793
- My intuition tells me otherwise.
- Why?

161
00:17:13,545 --> 00:17:16,964
No time for a lesson in civics,
my boy.

162
00:17:17,174 --> 00:17:19,426
In the 5th century BC
the citizens of Athens,

163
00:17:19,592 --> 00:17:23,221
having suffered under a tyrant,
managed to banish him.

164
00:17:23,431 --> 00:17:26,809
When he returned years later
with an army of mercenary,

165
00:17:26,976 --> 00:17:30,771
those same citizens
not only opened their gates for him,

166
00:17:30,938 --> 00:17:35,401
but stood by while he executed
members of the League of Government.

167
00:17:35,651 --> 00:17:41,574
Similar thing happened eight years ago
in a town called Indian Falls.

168
00:17:41,824 --> 00:17:47,747
I escaped death only through the intercession
of a lady of somewhat dubious reputation,

169
00:17:47,913 --> 00:17:52,127
and the cost of a very handsome ring
which once belonged to my mother.

170
00:17:52,294 --> 00:17:54,379
Unfortunately,
I have no more rings.

171
00:17:54,587 --> 00:17:59,175
- You're a judge.
- Been a judge many times and many towns.

172
00:17:59,467 --> 00:18:04,765
- I hope to live to be a judge again.
- I can't tell you what to do.

173
00:18:05,056 --> 00:18:07,920
Why must you be so stupid?
Have you forgotten what he is?

174
00:18:08,020 --> 00:18:11,020
Have you forgotten what he's done to people?
Forgotten that he's crazy?

175
00:18:11,230 --> 00:18:13,440
Don't you remember when he sat
in that chair and said:

176
00:18:13,690 --> 00:18:19,113
<i>''You'll never hang me. I'll come back
I swear it. I'll kill you, Kane!''</i>

177
00:18:26,412 --> 00:18:28,665
Here you are, ma'am.
This will take you to St. Louis.

178
00:18:28,831 --> 00:18:30,450
Thank you.

179
00:18:37,466 --> 00:18:41,094
Maybe you'd rather wait somewhere else.
Like at the hotel, maybe.

180
00:18:41,261 --> 00:18:44,514
- All right thank you.
- I'm sorry about all this, Mrs Kane.

181
00:18:44,724 --> 00:18:48,018
Don't you worry.
The Marshal'll take care of himself alright.

182
00:18:48,227 --> 00:18:50,687
Thank you
very much.

183
00:18:51,480 --> 00:18:53,815
Hey, that wasn't here
five years ago.

184
00:18:54,025 --> 00:18:58,487
- So what?
- Nothing...yet.

185
00:19:03,408 --> 00:19:08,080
Harvey, don't you think
Kane will be looking for you about now?

186
00:19:09,415 --> 00:19:12,760
- You're really sore at him.
- Wouldn't you be if you were me?

187
00:19:12,877 --> 00:19:16,089
I suppose...
if I were you.

188
00:19:24,181 --> 00:19:26,350
Be back in a little while.

189
00:19:46,996 --> 00:19:49,541
- Goodbye, Will
- Goodbye.

190
00:19:50,834 --> 00:19:53,002
- You think I'm letting you down, don't you?
- No.

191
00:19:54,129 --> 00:19:57,382
Look, this is just a dirty little village
in the middle of nowhere.

192
00:19:57,549 --> 00:20:00,803
Nothing that happens here
is really important. Now get out.

193
00:20:01,011 --> 00:20:02,760
There isn't time.

194
00:20:03,930 --> 00:20:07,016
What a waste.
Good luck.

195
00:20:18,571 --> 00:20:20,781
Johnny!

196
00:20:23,033 --> 00:20:26,537
- Why ain't you in church?
- Why ain't you?

197
00:20:26,787 --> 00:20:28,080
Will you do somethin'
for me?

198
00:20:28,289 --> 00:20:31,960
Go find Anderson, Howe and Fuller,
and tell them I want them here.

199
00:20:32,168 --> 00:20:35,797
- Then find Harv Pell!
- Don't have to do that. I'm right here.

200
00:20:35,964 --> 00:20:39,008
- Where have you been?
- Busy.

201
00:20:39,259 --> 00:20:41,720
You know what's doing?
We've got lots to do.

202
00:20:41,928 --> 00:20:45,723
Hold up a second.
This ain't really your job, you know.

203
00:20:45,933 --> 00:20:49,853
- That's what everybody keeps telling me.
- Just listen a second.

204
00:20:50,062 --> 00:20:54,275
- All right, I'm listening.
- This is the way I see it.

205
00:20:54,524 --> 00:20:59,739
If you'd gone with the new Marshal
not due till tomorrow, I'd be in charge, right?

206
00:21:00,490 --> 00:21:04,285
If I'm good enough to hold down the job
when there's trouble,

207
00:21:04,494 --> 00:21:06,788
how come the city fathers
didn't trust me with it permanently?

208
00:21:06,996 --> 00:21:09,458
- I don't know.
- Don't you?

209
00:21:09,665 --> 00:21:13,753
- No.
- I figure you carry a lot of weight.

210
00:21:13,963 --> 00:21:17,632
Maybe they didn't ask me.
Maybe they figured you were too young.

211
00:21:17,883 --> 00:21:21,553
- You think I'm too young too?
- You sure act like it sometimes. Come on.

212
00:21:30,855 --> 00:21:36,485
It's very simple, Will. You just tell
the old boys that I'm the new Marshal.

213
00:21:36,652 --> 00:21:40,322
Tomorrow they can tell the other fellow
sorry but that the job's filled.

214
00:21:40,532 --> 00:21:44,035
- You really mean it, don't you?
- Sure.

215
00:21:45,369 --> 00:21:48,789
- But I can't do it.
- Why not?

216
00:21:48,999 --> 00:21:52,544
- If you don't know, it's no use me tellin' you.
- You mean you won't do it?

217
00:21:52,752 --> 00:21:55,256
- Have it your way.
- All right

218
00:21:55,421 --> 00:21:59,760
The truth is, you probably
talked against me from the start.

219
00:21:59,926 --> 00:22:04,140
You've been sore about me
and Helen Ramirez right along, ain't you?

220
00:22:04,389 --> 00:22:07,476
You and Helen Ramirez?
I...

221
00:22:07,685 --> 00:22:12,397
It so happens I didn't know and it don't mean
anything to me, you ought to know that.

222
00:22:12,689 --> 00:22:14,692
Yeah, you've been washed up
for more than a year.

223
00:22:14,900 --> 00:22:19,572
You get married, only, you can't stand
anybody taking your place there...

224
00:22:19,780 --> 00:22:22,617
- ...especially me.
- You're...

225
00:22:28,622 --> 00:22:33,545
- I haven't got time, Harv.
- Okay, let's get down to business.

226
00:22:33,837 --> 00:22:36,090
You want me to stick,
you put a word in for me.

227
00:22:36,297 --> 00:22:40,635
Sure I want you to stick, but I'm not buying it.
It's gotta be up to you.

228
00:23:15,838 --> 00:23:18,550
I thought you'd grew up
by now.

229
00:23:18,800 --> 00:23:22,888
I thought your disposition might've
sweetened up a little down in Abilene.

230
00:23:23,054 --> 00:23:25,641
I guess we're both wrong.

231
00:23:32,606 --> 00:23:34,776
What's so funny?

232
00:23:35,026 --> 00:23:37,361
Did you really think
you could put that over on Kane?

233
00:23:37,570 --> 00:23:40,782
- Why not?
- When are you going to grow up?

234
00:23:40,949 --> 00:23:43,409
- I'm getting tired of that kind of talk.
- Then grow up.

235
00:23:43,660 --> 00:23:45,030
Cut it out!

236
00:23:50,625 --> 00:23:53,044
- All right
- Why should he have gone for it?

237
00:23:53,294 --> 00:23:56,090
He needs me plenty
when Frank Miller gets here.

238
00:23:56,340 --> 00:23:58,717
- That's possible.
- He should've had me made Marshal.

239
00:23:58,926 --> 00:24:02,722
- He's just sore. Sore about you and me.
- Is he?

240
00:24:02,888 --> 00:24:04,180
Sure.

241
00:24:04,348 --> 00:24:07,434
- You told him?
- Sure.

242
00:24:07,685 --> 00:24:09,978
You're a fool.

243
00:24:10,896 --> 00:24:13,899
Why?
Didn't you want him to know?

244
00:24:15,484 --> 00:24:20,572
Hey... Who did the walking out anyway,
you or him?

245
00:24:24,369 --> 00:24:26,829
Get out,
Harvey.

246
00:24:27,039 --> 00:24:29,666
- I might just do that.
- Then do it!

247
00:24:31,876 --> 00:24:34,420
- You don't mean that.
- Try me.

248
00:24:35,755 --> 00:24:38,258
You're gonna talk different
when Frank Miller gets here.

249
00:24:38,467 --> 00:24:41,345
You might want somebody around,
when you try to explain about Kane.

250
00:24:41,553 --> 00:24:44,265
- I can take care of myself.
- Sure.

251
00:24:44,432 --> 00:24:49,100
I've heard that you might not be so pretty
when he gets through with you.

252
00:24:52,315 --> 00:24:55,693
- I won't be back.
- Good.

253
00:25:03,860 --> 00:25:05,260
[Knock on door]

254
00:25:06,663 --> 00:25:08,665
Come in.

255
00:25:09,917 --> 00:25:15,798
- I just saw Harvey. Is everything alright?
- I think I have to talk with Mr Weaver.

256
00:25:17,216 --> 00:25:19,843
- You're getting out?
- Yes.

257
00:25:20,093 --> 00:25:23,014
You want me to give
Kane a hand?

258
00:25:28,478 --> 00:25:31,356
- No.
- All right.

259
00:25:41,616 --> 00:25:45,245
May I wait here
for the noon train?

260
00:25:46,997 --> 00:25:49,791
I said,
may I wait in the lobby until noon?

261
00:25:51,168 --> 00:25:54,462
- Sure, lady.
- Thank you.

262
00:25:56,215 --> 00:25:59,509
- You're Mrs Kane, ain't you?
- Yes.

263
00:25:59,676 --> 00:26:03,597
You're leaving on the noon train,
but your husband ain't.

264
00:26:04,265 --> 00:26:07,643
- No, why?
- No reason, but it's mighty interesting.

265
00:26:08,644 --> 00:26:12,815
Now me, I wouldn't leave this town at noon
for all the tea in China.

266
00:26:12,981 --> 00:26:16,318
No, sir.
It's going to be quite a sight to see.

267
00:26:23,310 --> 00:26:27,310
" Mine eyes have seen the glory
of the coming of the Lord; "

268
00:26:27,810 --> 00:26:31,810
" <i>he is trampling out the vintage
where the grapes of wrath are stored;</i> "

269
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:35,810
" <i>he hath loosed the fateful lightning
of his terrible swift sword;</i> "

270
00:26:36,210 --> 00:26:40,210
" <i>his truth is
marching ooon.</i> "

