Mildred, he's coming.
Now you do like I told you.

389
00:39:20,050 --> 00:39:22,890
I'm not home. Don't let him in.
No matter what he says, I'm not home.

390
00:39:23,090 --> 00:39:24,430
Sam, he's your friend.

391
00:39:24,530 --> 00:39:26,430
Don't argue with me. 
He'll be here in a second.

392
00:39:26,640 --> 00:39:28,770
He won't believe me.
He'll know I'm lying.

393
00:39:29,060 --> 00:39:30,770
You do as I tell you.

394
00:39:34,370 --> 00:39:35,770
[Knock on door]

395
00:39:47,370 --> 00:39:52,120
- Hello, Mrs Fuller. Is Sam in?
- No. No he isn't.

396
00:39:54,250 --> 00:39:57,710
Do you know where he is, Mrs Fuller?
It's important to me, to find him.

397
00:39:57,880 --> 00:40:02,340
I think... He's in church, Will.
He's gone to church.

398
00:40:04,470 --> 00:40:05,670
Without you?

399
00:40:05,770 --> 00:40:08,390
I'm gonna go in a little while,
as soon as I get dressed.

400
00:40:14,230 --> 00:40:17,610
Thank you, Mrs Fuller.
Goodbye.

401
00:40:40,980 --> 00:40:44,600
Well, what do you want?
Do you want me to get killed?

402
00:40:44,720 --> 00:40:47,100
Do you want to be a widow?
Is that what you want?

403
00:40:47,200 --> 00:40:49,270
No, Sam.
No.

404
00:40:50,060 --> 00:40:51,310
Kane!

405
00:40:53,810 --> 00:40:57,860
- What's the matter, Jimmy?
- Nothin'. I've been lookin' for you.

406
00:40:58,110 --> 00:41:01,780
I wanna a gun. I wanna be with you
when that train comes in.

407
00:41:02,570 --> 00:41:07,330
- Can...can you handle a gun?
- Sure I can. I used to be good.

408
00:41:07,530 --> 00:41:10,160
Honest.
It ain't just gettin' even.

409
00:41:10,370 --> 00:41:14,330
It's a chance. This is what I need.
Please Kane, let me get in on this.

410
00:41:15,290 --> 00:41:18,970
All right, Jimmy.
I'll call you if I need you.

411
00:41:19,130 --> 00:41:21,470
Get yourself a drink
meanwhile.

412
00:41:29,940 --> 00:41:31,140
[Knock on door]

413
00:41:31,440 --> 00:41:32,860
Come in,
Sam.

414
00:41:40,700 --> 00:41:42,780
You're leavin' town?

415
00:41:43,950 --> 00:41:47,450
- Where are you going?
- I don't know yet.

416
00:41:47,620 --> 00:41:50,370
This doesn't make much sense.

417
00:41:53,000 --> 00:41:56,000
- You're afraid, huh? 
Afraid of Miller.

418
00:41:56,210 --> 00:41:57,210
No.

419
00:41:57,420 --> 00:41:59,550
Sure you are.
You wouldn't be runnin'.

420
00:41:59,720 --> 00:42:02,840
You don't have to worry about as long as 
I'm around, you know that.

421
00:42:03,090 --> 00:42:05,940
I'm not scared of Miller. 
I'll take him on any time.

422
00:42:06,000 --> 00:42:07,140
I believe you.

423
00:42:07,310 --> 00:42:11,140
Then why are you goin'?
You're cuttin' out with Kane.

424
00:42:11,390 --> 00:42:12,940
- Oh, Harvey...
- Why are you goin'?

425
00:42:13,150 --> 00:42:15,360
- What difference does it make?
- It's Kane! I know it's Kane!

426
00:42:15,610 --> 00:42:20,860
It isn't Kane. I'm going to tell you something
about you and your friend Kane.

427
00:42:21,030 --> 00:42:24,200
You're a good-looking boy,
you have big broad shoulders.

428
00:42:24,370 --> 00:42:26,080
But he is a man.

429
00:42:26,330 --> 00:42:29,000
It takes more than broad shoulders
to make a man, Harvey,

430
00:42:29,200 --> 00:42:31,410
and you have a
long way to go.

431
00:42:33,250 --> 00:42:36,380
You know something?
I don't think you'll ever make it.

432
00:42:38,590 --> 00:42:40,840
Let me tell you something.
You're not goin' anywhere.

433
00:42:41,090 --> 00:42:44,760
You're stayin' with me.
It's gonna be just like it was before.

434
00:42:49,390 --> 00:42:52,190
You want to know why I'm leaving?
Then listen.

435
00:42:52,400 --> 00:42:56,690
Kane will be a dead man in half an hour.
And nobody's going to do anything about it.

436
00:42:56,940 --> 00:43:01,110
And when he dies, this town dies too.
I can feel it.

437
00:43:01,280 --> 00:43:04,780
I'm all alone in the world,
I have to make a living.

438
00:43:04,990 --> 00:43:08,000
So I'm going someplace else,
that's all.

439
00:43:11,410 --> 00:43:16,170
And as for you, I don't like anybody to put
his hands on me unless I want him to.

440
00:43:16,380 --> 00:43:19,220
And I don't like you to
...anymore.

441
00:43:22,220 --> 00:43:24,720
" <i>He made a vow
while in state prison</i> "

442
00:43:25,220 --> 00:43:27,720
" <i>Vowed it would be my life
or his'n</i>  "

443
00:43:28,220 --> 00:43:30,720
" <i>I'm not afraid of death
but oh</i> "

444
00:43:31,220 --> 00:43:35,720
" <i>What will I do
if you leeeave me?</i> "

445
00:43:35,900 --> 00:43:39,650
Our text today
is from Malachi, chapter four.

446
00:43:39,860 --> 00:43:46,700
<i>''For, behold, the day cometh, that shall burn
as an oven; and all the proud, yea, and all..''</i>

447
00:43:52,210 --> 00:43:53,540
Yes?

448
00:43:53,750 --> 00:43:57,050
I'm sorry, parson,
I don't want to disturb the services...

449
00:43:57,250 --> 00:44:01,840
You already have. You don't
come to this church very often, Marshal.

450
00:44:02,090 --> 00:44:05,300
When you got married today
you didn't see fit to be married here.

451
00:44:05,470 --> 00:44:09,180
What can be so important
to bring you here now?

452
00:44:09,390 --> 00:44:11,730
I need help.

453
00:44:15,980 --> 00:44:20,070
It's true, I haven't been a churchgoing man,
and maybe that's a bad thing.

454
00:44:20,280 --> 00:44:24,280
I didn't get married here today
because my wife is a Quaker.

455
00:44:24,450 --> 00:44:28,370
But I came here for help
because there are people here.

456
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:34,000
I'm sorry, Marshal.
Say what you have to say.

457
00:44:35,960 --> 00:44:39,550
Maybe some of you already know it,
but if you don't...

458
00:44:39,760 --> 00:44:42,720
It looks like Frank Miller
is coming back on the noon train.

459
00:44:46,510 --> 00:44:49,850
I need all the special deputies
I can get.

460
00:44:55,070 --> 00:44:57,280
Well,
what are we waiting for?

461
00:44:58,940 --> 00:45:00,950
Let's go.

462
00:45:01,910 --> 00:45:04,160
Hold it a minute,
hold it!

463
00:45:04,370 --> 00:45:07,160
Before we rush out into something
that isn't going to be so pleasant,

464
00:45:07,370 --> 00:45:10,160
let's make sure we know
what this is all about.

465
00:45:11,170 --> 00:45:16,000
What I want to know is this. Ain't it true
that Kane ain't no longer a Marshal?

466
00:45:17,420 --> 00:45:20,970
And ain't it true there is personal trouble
between Kane and Miller?

467
00:45:25,760 --> 00:45:29,390
All right, alright!
Quiet, everybody!

468
00:45:29,600 --> 00:45:32,520
If there's a difference of opinion,
let everybody have a say.

469
00:45:32,770 --> 00:45:36,980
But let's do it like grown-up people,
and let's get the kids out of the building.

470
00:46:09,140 --> 00:46:13,060
- Anything on the train?
- It's on time as far as I know, sir.

471
00:46:18,030 --> 00:46:20,130
I say it don't really matter 
if there's anything...

472
00:46:20,230 --> 00:46:22,530
personal between Miller 
and the Marshal, here.

473
00:46:22,740 --> 00:46:25,330
We all know who Miller is,
and what Miller is.

474
00:46:25,490 --> 00:46:30,330
- What's more, we're wasting time.
- All right Coy!

475
00:46:31,000 --> 00:46:34,670
Yes, we all know who Miller is
and we put him away once.

476
00:46:34,920 --> 00:46:38,210
And who saved him from hanging?
The politicians up north.

477
00:46:38,420 --> 00:46:42,010
I say, this is their mess.
Let them take care of it.

478
00:46:42,220 --> 00:46:44,510
- Fryer?
- Well, I say this:

479
00:46:44,720 --> 00:46:47,930
We've been paying good money all along
for a Marshal and deputies.

480
00:46:48,180 --> 00:46:51,940
The first time there's any trouble,
we're supposed to take care of it ourselves.

481
00:46:52,150 --> 00:46:54,110
What have we been paying for
all this time?

482
00:46:54,310 --> 00:46:57,650
I say we're not peace officers,
and this ain't our job!

483
00:46:58,990 --> 00:47:01,780
I've been saying right along,
we ought to have more deputies.

484
00:47:01,990 --> 00:47:05,660
If we did,
we wouldn't be facing this thing, now.

485
00:47:05,830 --> 00:47:09,500
Just a minute, just a minute!
Everybody, quiet!

486
00:47:09,660 --> 00:47:12,420
Keep it orderly.
You had your hand up, Ezra?

487
00:47:13,420 --> 00:47:15,840
I can't believe I've heard
some of the things said here.

488
00:47:16,050 --> 00:47:17,800
You ought to be
ashamed of yourselves.

489
00:47:18,010 --> 00:47:21,300
Sure, we paid this man,
and he was the best Marshal we ever had.

490
00:47:21,510 --> 00:47:23,640
It ain't his trouble,
it's ours.

491
00:47:23,840 --> 00:47:26,850
If we don't do what's right,
we're gonna have plenty more trouble.

492
00:47:27,020 --> 00:47:30,980
There ain't but one thing to do now,
and you all know what that is.

493
00:47:31,190 --> 00:47:34,520
- Go ahead, Kibbee.
- This thing has been handled wrong.

494
00:47:34,730 --> 00:47:37,650
Those three killers
walking the streets bold as brass...

495
00:47:37,860 --> 00:47:41,360
Why didn't you put them in jail
where they ought to be?

496
00:47:41,570 --> 00:47:44,120
Then we'd only have Miller to worry about
instead of the four.

497
00:47:44,330 --> 00:47:48,330
I haven't anything to arrest them for.
They haven't done anything.

498
00:47:48,540 --> 00:47:51,210
There's no law against them
sitting on a bench at the depot.

499
00:47:52,170 --> 00:47:56,130
I can't listen to any more of this.
What's the matter with you people?

500
00:47:56,340 --> 00:47:58,200
Don'tca remember when 
a decent woman

501
00:47:58,300 --> 00:48:00,300
couldn't walk down the street 
in broad daylight?

502
00:48:00,510 --> 00:48:03,720
Don'tca remember when this wasn't a fit place
to bring up a child?

503
00:48:03,970 --> 00:48:07,600
How can you sit here, and talk, and talk,
and talk like this?

504
00:48:07,810 --> 00:48:12,190
What are we getting so excited about?
How do we know Miller's on that train?

505
00:48:12,980 --> 00:48:17,780
We can be pretty sure he's on it.
Time's getting short.

506
00:48:19,110 --> 00:48:23,490
- Parson, you got anything to say?
- I don't know.

507
00:48:23,700 --> 00:48:26,410
The commandment says
<i>''thou shalt not kill''</i>

508
00:48:26,660 --> 00:48:29,290
but we hire men to go out
and do it for us.

509
00:48:29,500 --> 00:48:32,710
The right and the wrong
seem pretty clear here,

510
00:48:32,880 --> 00:48:35,550
but if you're asking me to tell my people
to go out and kill,

511
00:48:35,750 --> 00:48:42,890
and maybe get themselves killed, I'm sorry,
I don't know what to say. I'm sorry.

512
00:48:43,680 --> 00:48:46,010
All right,
I'll say this.

513
00:48:46,180 --> 00:48:51,230
What this town owes Will Kane, it can never
pay with money. Don't ever forget it.

514
00:48:51,440 --> 00:48:55,270
He's the best Marshal we've ever had,
and maybe the best we'll ever have.

515
00:48:55,440 --> 00:49:00,030
So if Miller comes back here today,
it's our problem, not his.

516
00:49:00,200 --> 00:49:03,160
It's our problem
because this is our town.

517
00:49:03,410 --> 00:49:05,660
We made it with our own hands,
out of nothing.

518
00:49:05,830 --> 00:49:10,160
If we want to keep it decent
we gotta think mighty clear today.

519
00:49:10,370 --> 00:49:14,840
We gotta have the courage to do what is right,
no matter how hard it is.

520
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:19,720
All right! There's gonna be fighting
when Kane and Miller meet.

521
00:49:19,920 --> 00:49:23,100
And somebody's going to get hurt,
that's for sure.

522
00:49:23,300 --> 00:49:27,930
Now...
People up north are thinking about this town.

523
00:49:28,140 --> 00:49:34,310
Thinking about sending money down here,
to put up stores and factories.

524
00:49:34,520 --> 00:49:37,820
It would mean a lot to this town,
an awful lot.

525
00:49:38,030 --> 00:49:43,990
But if they'll read about shooting in the streets,
what are they going to think?

526
00:49:44,200 --> 00:49:48,950
I'll tell you. They'll think
this is just another wide-open town,

527
00:49:49,210 --> 00:49:51,790
and everything we worked for
will be wiped out.

528
00:49:51,960 --> 00:49:56,920
In one day, this town
will be sat back five years.

529
00:49:57,090 --> 00:49:59,760
And I don't think
we can let that happen.

530
00:49:59,920 --> 00:50:03,640
Mind you, you all know
how I feel about this man.

531
00:50:03,850 --> 00:50:08,980
He's a mighty brave man, a good man.
He didn't have to come back here today.

532
00:50:09,850 --> 00:50:14,900
And for his sake, and a sake of this town,
I wish he hadn't.

533
00:50:15,150 --> 00:50:17,360
Because if he's not here
when Miller comes,

534
00:50:17,570 --> 00:50:20,740
my hunch is,
there won't be any trouble, not one bit.

535
00:50:20,900 --> 00:50:25,870
Tomorrow we'll have a new Marshal
and if we offer him our services,

536
00:50:25,990 --> 00:50:28,200
I think we can handle anything
that comes along.

537
00:50:29,330 --> 00:50:34,000
To me that makes sense.
To me that's the only way out of this.

538
00:50:35,800 --> 00:50:40,010
Will, I think you better go
while there's still time.

539
00:50:41,590 --> 00:50:44,760
It's better for you and...
it's better for us.

540
00:50:55,150 --> 00:50:56,440
Thanks.

541
00:51:22,810 --> 00:51:26,610
[Playing tune on harmonica]

542
00:51:26,810 --> 00:51:29,140
Why don't you put
that thing away?

543
00:51:44,530 --> 00:51:47,830
- Bang, bang, bang!
- You're dead, Kane.

544
00:51:53,330 --> 00:51:55,830
"<i>Do not forsake me,
oh, my darlin',</i>"

545
00:51:57,830 --> 00:52:02,830
" <i>On this,
our wedding daaayyy.</i>"

546
00:52:03,230 --> 00:52:08,230
" <i>Do not forsake me,
oh, my daaarlin',</i> "

547
00:52:08,330 --> 00:52:14,730
" <i>Waaait;
wait alone.</i> "

548
00:52:25,990 --> 00:52:29,160
I just sent the kid to find you.
Didn't he come?

549
00:52:29,330 --> 00:52:31,960
He was here.

550
00:52:34,290 --> 00:52:37,210
You've been my friend all my life.
You got me this job.

551
00:52:37,380 --> 00:52:40,050
You made them
send for me.

552
00:52:40,300 --> 00:52:43,590
Ever since I was a kid
I wanted to be like you, Mart.

553
00:52:43,800 --> 00:52:49,640
- You've been a law man all your life.
- Yeah, all my life. It's a great life.

554
00:52:49,850 --> 00:52:52,810
You risk your skin catching killers,
and the juries turn them loose,

555
00:52:52,980 --> 00:52:55,650
so they can come back,
and shoot at you again.

556
00:52:55,860 --> 00:52:58,570
If you're honest,
you're poor your whole life.

557
00:52:58,780 --> 00:53:02,950
And in the end you wind up dying all alone
on some dirty street.

558
00:53:03,120 --> 00:53:08,160
For what?
For nothing. For a tin star.

559
00:53:08,370 --> 00:53:13,290
Listen, the judge's left town, Harvey's quit,
and I'm having trouble getting deputies.

560
00:53:13,500 --> 00:53:16,500
It figures.
It's all happening too sudden.

561
00:53:16,800 --> 00:53:21,300
People got to talk themselves into law and 
order before they do anything about it.

562
00:53:21,590 --> 00:53:26,430
Maybe because down deep they don't care.
They just don't care.

563
00:53:32,770 --> 00:53:35,230
What'll I do,
Mart?

564
00:53:37,400 --> 00:53:39,940
I was hopin' you
wouldn't come back.

565
00:53:40,200 --> 00:53:44,660
- You know why I came back.
- But not to commit suicide.

566
00:53:44,870 --> 00:53:48,410
Sometimes... 
Sometimes prison changes a man.

567
00:53:48,580 --> 00:53:53,460
Not him. This is all planned,
that's why they're all here.

568
00:53:53,670 --> 00:53:56,380
Get out, Will!
Get out.

569
00:54:07,270 --> 00:54:09,430
Will you come down
to that depot with me?

570
00:54:09,600 --> 00:54:11,890
No.

571
00:54:12,900 --> 00:54:17,320
You know how I feel about you,
but I ain't goin' with you.

572
00:54:17,490 --> 00:54:22,030
Seems like a man with busted knuckles
didn't need arthritis too, don't it?

573
00:54:22,990 --> 00:54:24,910
No,
I couldn't do nothin' for you.

574
00:54:25,200 --> 00:54:29,870
You'd be worried about me.
You'd get yourself killed worryin' about me.

575
00:54:30,080 --> 00:54:32,250
It's too one-sided
like it is.

576
00:54:38,550 --> 00:54:41,140
- So long, Martin.
- So long.

577
00:54:42,680 --> 00:54:46,850
It's all for nothin', Will.
It's all for nothin'.

578
00:54:58,070 --> 00:55:02,240
Excuse me,
what is Mrs Ramirez's room number?

579
00:55:03,530 --> 00:55:06,120
- Three.
- Thank you.

580
00:55:23,010 --> 00:55:25,390
Come in.

581
00:55:27,680 --> 00:55:31,980
- Yes?
- Mrs Ramirez? I'm Mrs Kane.

582
00:55:32,190 --> 00:55:34,270
I know.

583
00:55:35,570 --> 00:55:38,820
- May I come in?
- If you like.

584
00:55:44,370 --> 00:55:47,330
- Sit down, Mrs Kane.
- No, thank you.

585
00:55:47,540 --> 00:55:49,460
- What do you want?
- Please...

586
00:55:49,660 --> 00:55:52,790
It's just I'm afraid that if I sat down,
I wouldn't be able to get up again.

587
00:55:53,040 --> 00:55:56,050
- Why?
- It wasn't easy for me to come here.

588
00:55:56,250 --> 00:55:59,380
- Why?
- Look, Mrs Ramirez...

589
00:55:59,550 --> 00:56:03,970
Will and I were married an hour ago.
We were all packed and ready to leave...

590
00:56:04,140 --> 00:56:06,430
...then this thing happened
and he wouldn't go.

591
00:56:06,600 --> 00:56:11,690
I did everything. I pleaded, I threatened,
I just couldn't reach him.

592
00:56:11,900 --> 00:56:16,400
- And now?
- That man downstairs, the clerk..

593
00:56:16,610 --> 00:56:19,320
He said things about you
and Will

594
00:56:19,570 --> 00:56:22,070
I've tried to understand
why he wouldn't go with me,

595
00:56:22,320 --> 00:56:25,240
and it's got to be because of you.

596
00:56:25,870 --> 00:56:28,620
- What do you want from me?
- Let him go.

597
00:56:28,790 --> 00:56:30,960
He still has a chance.
Let him go.

598
00:56:31,250 --> 00:56:34,670
- I can not help you.
- Please.

599
00:56:34,880 --> 00:56:37,170
He isn't staying
for me.

600
00:56:37,380 --> 00:56:41,050
I haven't spoken to him for a year,
until today.

601
00:56:44,140 --> 00:56:48,730
- I'm leaving on the same train you are.
- Then why is he staying?

602
00:56:49,730 --> 00:56:53,400
If you don't know,
I can not explain it to you.

603
00:56:55,650 --> 00:56:58,900
Thank you anyway.
You've been very kind.

604
00:57:01,070 --> 00:57:05,450
What kind of woman are you?
How can you leave him like this?

605
00:57:05,660 --> 00:57:08,200
Does the sound of guns
frighten you that much?

606
00:57:08,450 --> 00:57:11,630
No, Mrs Ramirez.
I've heard guns.

607
00:57:11,830 --> 00:57:14,790
My father and my brother
were killed by guns.

608
00:57:15,000 --> 00:57:19,260
They were on the right side, but that
didn't help them when the shooting started..

609
00:57:19,420 --> 00:57:23,100
My brother was 19.
I watched him die.

610
00:57:23,850 --> 00:57:29,270
That's when I became a Quaker.
I don't care who's right or who's wrong.

611
00:57:29,480 --> 00:57:33,360
There's got to be some better way
for people to live.

612
00:57:35,520 --> 00:57:38,690
Will knows how I feel about it.

613
00:57:38,900 --> 00:57:43,120
Just a minute. Are you going to wait 
for the train downstairs?

614
00:57:43,370 --> 00:57:46,740
- Yes.
- Why don't you wait here?

615
00:57:48,240 --> 00:57:51,740
"<i>Do not forsake me,
oh, my darlin',</i>"

616
00:57:53,740 --> 00:57:58,740
" <i>On this,
our wedding daaayyy.</i>"

617
00:57:58,740 --> 00:58:02,370
" <i>Do not forsake me,
oh, my daaarlin',</i> "

618
00:58:02,470 --> 00:58:05,760
I've got no use for Kane,
but he's got guts.

619
00:58:06,010 --> 00:58:08,730
You're mighty broadminded, 
Joe.

620
00:58:12,650 --> 00:58:14,670
How about you? I always figured you had guts,


621
00:58:14,770 --> 00:58:17,070
but I never gave you credit for brains, 
until now.

622
00:58:17,280 --> 00:58:20,820
What does that mean?

623
00:58:21,030 --> 00:58:24,080
It takes a smart man
to know when to back away.

624
00:58:26,200 --> 00:58:28,230
If I can't pick my company 
when I drink in here,

625
00:58:28,330 --> 00:58:29,830
I ain't coming in here anymore.

626
00:58:31,790 --> 00:58:37,710
Okay... All right
The boy with a tin star.

627
00:58:43,710 --> 00:58:46,710
Bartender: All right boys, 
what are you gonna have?

628
01:00:04,510 --> 01:00:08,310
Put a saddle on him, Kane.
Go on, saddle him up.

629
01:00:08,520 --> 01:00:10,770
He'd go a long way
before he tires.

630
01:00:11,020 --> 01:00:13,310
- That's what you were thinking, wasn't it?
- Kind of.

631
01:00:13,480 --> 01:00:15,090
You're scared?

632
01:00:15,890 --> 01:00:17,190
I guess so.

633
01:00:19,280 --> 01:00:21,660
Sure.
Stands to reason.

634
01:00:24,740 --> 01:00:27,410
Come on.
Let me help you.

635
01:00:33,960 --> 01:00:38,340
Seems like all everybody and his brother
wants is to get me out of town.

636
01:00:38,550 --> 01:00:41,680
Nobody wants to
see you get killed.

637
01:00:42,730 --> 01:00:43,730
Where're you going?

638
01:00:43,830 --> 01:00:45,140
I don't know.
Back to the office, I guess.

639
01:00:45,310 --> 01:00:48,270
Oh, no. You're getting on that horse
and getting out.

640
01:00:49,180 --> 01:00:51,180
What's the matter with you?

641
01:00:51,330 --> 01:00:53,730
You were ready to do it yourself.
You said so.

642
01:00:53,860 --> 01:00:57,570
Look, Harv. I thought about it
because I was tired.

643
01:00:57,740 --> 01:01:01,570
You think about a lot of things
when you're tired. But I can't do it.

644
01:01:01,740 --> 01:01:04,870
- Why?
- I don't know.

645
01:01:05,080 --> 01:01:07,450
Get on that horse, 
Will!

646
01:01:08,450 --> 01:01:11,170
Why is this so important?
You don't care if I live or die.

647
01:01:11,750 --> 01:01:12,840
Come on.

648
01:01:12,990 --> 01:01:16,840
Don't shove me, Harv. 
I'm tired of being shoved.

649
01:03:01,490 --> 01:03:05,660
I hate this town.
I've always hated it.

650
01:03:05,830 --> 01:03:09,000
To be a Mexican woman
in a town like this...

651
01:03:09,210 --> 01:03:13,380
- I understand.
- You do?

652
01:03:13,580 --> 01:03:18,670
That's good. I don't understand you,
no matter what you say.

653
01:03:18,840 --> 01:03:22,510
If Kane was my man,
I'd never leave him. I'd get a gun.

654
01:03:22,680 --> 01:03:24,970
- I'd fight
- Why don't you?

655
01:03:26,810 --> 01:03:29,520
He's not my man.
He's yours.

656
01:03:32,620 --> 01:03:35,120
" <i>Vowed it would be my life
or his'n</i>  "

657
01:03:35,620 --> 01:03:37,520
" <i>I'm not afraid of death
but oh</i> "

658
01:03:38,020 --> 01:03:44,520
" <i>What will I do
if you leeeave me?</i> "

659
01:03:44,720 --> 01:03:48,520
" <i>Do not forsake me,
oh my darlin' </i>"

660
01:03:49,540 --> 01:03:55,050
- You have some clean water I can use?
- Why, sure, Marshal sit down.

661
01:04:03,010 --> 01:04:07,220
- Running some kind of trouble, Marshal?
- No, no trouble.

